│ stop({"edit_points": [[15246, 15248, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe issue is that the SLP  │
│ vectorizer is incorrectly vectorizing calls to llvm.abs.i64 with the second argument (is_int_min_poison) set to true, but when it creates the vectorized version │
│ llvm.abs.v2i32, it's passing false as the second argument instead of preserving the original value.\n\nIn the source code, both abs calls have the second        │
│ argument as true (i1 true), meaning they should return poison if the input is INT_MIN. However, in the vectorized version, the second argument is set to false   │
│ (i1 false), which changes the semantics - it will return INT_MIN instead of poison for INT_MIN inputs.\n\nThis causes a semantic mismatch because the original   │
│ 64-bit computations when truncated to 32-bit can produce negative values that are then passed to abs. In the original code, abs is called on 64-bit positive     │
│ values (due to zext and multiplication), so the second argument being true doesn't matter. But in the vectorized version, the computation is done in 32-bit,     │
│ which can overflow and produce negative values, and then abs is called with is_int_min_poison=false, giving different results.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s           │
│ Log:\n\nThe opt log shows that the SLP vectorizer successfully builds a tree of operations and decides to vectorize at cost -2. The key observation is in the    │
│ debug output where it shows:\n\n```\n%4 = call <2 x i32> @llvm.abs.v2i32(<2 x i32> %3, i1 false)\n```\n\nThe second argument is false, whereas in the original   │
│ it was true. This indicates the vectorizer is not preserving the scalar argument correctly.\n\nLooking at the SLP vectorizer code around line 15246, there's     │
│ logic that specifically handles the abs intrinsic when bitwidth reduction occurs, forcing the second argument to false.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe root   │
│ cause is in the SLP vectorizer's handling of the llvm.abs intrinsic when performing bitwidth reduction. The code at lines 15246-15248 unconditionally sets the   │
│ second argument to false when MinBWs contains an entry for the abs intrinsic and the bitwidth is being reduced.\n\nHowever, this is incorrect because:\n1. The   │
│ original abs calls are on 64-bit values with is_int_min_poison=true\n2. The vectorized version operates on 32-bit values \n3. The semantic meaning of            │
│ is_int_min_poison=true vs false is different\n4. The optimization assumes that reducing bitwidth requires changing the poison behavior, but this isn't always    │
│ safe\n\nThe issue is that the vectorizer is changing the semantics of the abs operation by altering the is_int_min_poison flag without considering whether this  │
│ preserves the original program behavior.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe problematic code is at lines 15246-15248 in                                        │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp. This code unconditionally sets the second argument of abs to false when bitwidth reduction occurs. Instead, it  │
│ should preserve the original scalar argument value to maintain semantic equivalence.\n\nThe fix is to remove this special handling for the abs intrinsic's       │
│ second argument, allowing it to be vectorized like any other scalar argument.\n\n5. Conclusion:\n\nBy removing the special case that forces the                  │
│ is_int_min_poison argument to false during bitwidth reduction, the vectorizer will preserve the original semantics of the abs intrinsic calls. This ensures that │
│ the vectorized code produces the same results as the scalar code, fixing the verification failure observed in the reproducer."})                                 │
