│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                                                                                                  │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The issue is that the SLP vectorizer is incorrectly vectorizing calls to llvm.abs.i64 with the second argument (is_int_min_poison) set to true, but when it      │
│ creates the vectorized version llvm.abs.v2i32, it's passing false as the second argument instead of preserving the original value.                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ In the source code, both abs calls have the second argument as true (i1 true), meaning they should return poison if the input is INT_MIN. However, in the        │
│ vectorized version, the second argument is set to false (i1 false), which changes the semantics - it will return INT_MIN instead of poison for INT_MIN inputs.   │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ This causes a semantic mismatch because the original 64-bit computations when truncated to 32-bit can produce negative values that are then passed to abs. In    │
│ the original code, abs is called on 64-bit positive values (due to zext and multiplication), so the second argument being true doesn't matter. But in the        │
│ vectorized version, the computation is done in 32-bit, which can overflow and produce negative values, and then abs is called with is_int_min_poison=false,      │
│ giving different results.                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The opt log shows that the SLP vectorizer successfully builds a tree of operations and decides to vectorize at cost -2. The key observation is in the debug      │
│ output where it shows:                                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                              │
│ %4 = call <2 x i32> @llvm.abs.v2i32(<2 x i32> %3, i1 false)                                                                                                      │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The second argument is false, whereas in the original it was true. This indicates the vectorizer is not preserving the scalar argument correctly.                │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ Looking at the SLP vectorizer code around line 15246, there's logic that specifically handles the abs intrinsic when bitwidth reduction occurs, forcing the      │
│ second argument to false.                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The root cause is in the SLP vectorizer's handling of the llvm.abs intrinsic when performing bitwidth reduction. The code at lines 15246-15248 unconditionally   │
│ sets the second argument to false when MinBWs contains an entry for the abs intrinsic and the bitwidth is being reduced.                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ However, this is incorrect because:                                                                                                                              │
│ 1. The original abs calls are on 64-bit values with is_int_min_poison=true                                                                                       │
│ 2. The vectorized version operates on 32-bit values                                                                                                              │
│ 3. The semantic meaning of is_int_min_poison=true vs false is different                                                                                          │
│ 4. The optimization assumes that reducing bitwidth requires changing the poison behavior, but this isn't always safe                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The issue is that the vectorizer is changing the semantics of the abs operation by altering the is_int_min_poison flag without considering whether this          │
│ preserves the original program behavior.                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The problematic code is at lines 15246-15248 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp. This code unconditionally sets the second argument of abs to    │
│ false when bitwidth reduction occurs. Instead, it should preserve the original scalar argument value to maintain semantic equivalence.                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The fix is to remove this special handling for the abs intrinsic's second argument, allowing it to be vectorized like any other scalar argument.                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ By removing the special case that forces the is_int_min_poison argument to false during bitwidth reduction, the vectorizer will preserve the original semantics  │
│ of the abs intrinsic calls. This ensures that the vectorized code produces the same results as the scalar code, fixing the verification failure observed in the  │
│ reproducer.                                                                                                                                                      │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                                                                                                  │
